Commentary:
In terms of the broader analysis across all models, (I could be wrong here - and this is just observations from memory/experience and not extensive analysis)

At a bird's eye view, it seems that previous batch of schemas were trained on the seed, but this batch has been trained on seed and secondary papers

Most of these schemas tend to follow similar structures: variants/properties, then elaborate sections of stimuli, effect, etc. 

Thinking constructs/reasoning models seem to have non-flat hierarchies aka taxonomies than non-reasoning models. 

Larger models tend to overspecify/introduce redundancy than smaller models.

Large reasoning models capture subtle information than small non-thinking models aka information that is not repeatedly reinforced across papers 
but rather have a passing reference in fewer papers. Including covariate information on influencing parameters

However, unsurprisingly, implicit information is not captured by any of the models - like all errors are not equal in stroop. 
Most papers do not mention this as it is deemed obvious to those who work in the field and because the brain is not yet well 
parcellated to deem how manifested errors show up cogntively. 
